{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.09,0.13,0.42,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62006"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47452"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8223"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62006"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Endocrine Clinic with a two-month history of an enlarging neck lump. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies difficulty swallowing, voice changes, or weight loss. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm firm, mobile nodule in the right lobe of the thyroid. No cervical lymphadenopathy is detected. Thyroid function tests are normal. Ultrasound shows a 3 cm solitary nodule in the right thyroid lobe with no suspicious features in the remainder of the gland. Ultrasound-guided fine needle aspiration cytology reports Bethesda category 4 (follicular neoplasm).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staging CT head/neck/chest","Repeat ultrasound in 3 months","Core biopsy of thyroid nodule","Right hemithyroidectomy","Total thyroidectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a thyroid nodule that has been classified as Bethesda category 4 (follicular neoplasm) on fine needle aspiration cytology. The Bethesda System for Reporting Thyroid Cytopathology includes six categories with corresponding malignancy risks: Category 1 (non-diagnostic, 5-10% risk), Category 2 (benign, 0-3% risk), Category 3 (atypia of undetermined significance, 10-30% risk), Category 4 (follicular neoplasm, 20-30% risk), Category 5 (suspicious for malignancy, 60-75% risk), and Category 6 (malignant, 97-99% risk). For Category 4, cytology alone cannot distinguish between follicular adenoma and follicular carcinoma as this requires assessment of capsular and vascular invasion on histology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight hemithyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as it provides both diagnostic information and potential definitive treatment. If histology confirms malignancy, completion thyroidectomy may be considered based on risk factors and multidisciplinary team discussion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaging CT head/neck/chest\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage as malignancy has not been confirmed, and CT would not alter the need for diagnostic surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 3 months\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for Bethesda category 2 (benign) nodules but is insufficient for category 4 lesions where there is a significant risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECore biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E of thyroid nodules is not routinely recommended as it carries higher risks than FNA and still cannot provide the histological assessment needed to diagnose follicular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal thyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive as initial management since 70-80% of Bethesda 4 nodules prove benign on final histology. It would expose patients unnecessarily to the risks of total thyroidectomy and lifelong thyroid replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bethesda category 4 (follicular neoplasm) on thyroid FNA has a 20-30% risk of malignancy and requires diagnostic hemithyroidectomy.","Core biopsy is not indicated in the investigation of thyroid nodules as it cannot distinguish between follicular adenoma and carcinoma.","Total thyroidectomy is not appropriate first-line management for Bethesda 4 lesions as most will prove benign on histology."],"references":["Cabanillas ME, McFadden DG, Durante C. Thyroid cancer. Lancet 2016; 2016;388:2783-95. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27240885/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47452"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47452"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T00:19:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T00:21:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"730"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links